\describe{
\item{\code{na.bridge = FALSE} (default)}{The input is passed to the
underlying TA-Lib C routine as-is. Because most indicators smooth
across time (EMA, RSI, MACD, Bollinger Bands, ...), a single
\code{NA} in the input typically propagates forward and \strong{poisons
every subsequent value} - it is common for one missing
observation to produce an output that is entirely \code{NA} from that
position onward. This mode is the right choice when you want to
\emph{see} the missing data in the output rather than silently
compute around it.}
\item{\code{na.bridge = TRUE}}{\code{NA} rows are stripped from the input
before the C routine runs; the indicator is computed on the
resulting dense series; results are then re-expanded to the
original length with \code{NA} inserted at every position the input
had \code{NA}. Output length always matches input length, so the
result can be joined back to the source \code{data.frame} by row.

\strong{Consequence to understand before enabling:} bridging causes
the indicator to treat non-consecutive observations as
consecutive. A 14-period RSI with \code{na.bridge = TRUE} over a
series containing a month-long gap will compute using 14
observations that span several real-world months as if they were
14 adjacent trading days. For sparse missing values (e.g. a
single missing tick) this is harmless; for clustered gaps (e.g.
a delisted period, a weekend encoded as \code{NA}) the output is
correctly aligned \emph{by position} but economically meaningless
across the gap. Inspect gap structure with \code{which(is.na(x))}
before enabling on low-quality time series.}
